          "title": "The psalm's place in the Songs of Ascent — a pilgrim reorientation",
          "body": "The Songs of Ascent (Psalms 120-134) were sung by pilgrims ascending to Jerusalem for the three major feasts. The collection moves from alienation (120:5-7) to arrival and blessing (134:3), but Psalm 127 — the structural center — performs a crucial reorientation. The pilgrims are going home to their houses, cities, and families after worship; this psalm recalibrates every homecoming. The house they return to stands because Yahweh built it. The city they enter is guarded because Yahweh guards it. The children who meet them at the door are nachalah from Yahweh. Worship in Jerusalem is not the interruption of real life; it is the interpretive key to all of real life. The Songs of Ascent do not separate sacred and secular — they subordinate every secular sphere to Yahweh's sovereign provision. Psalm 127 makes that subordination explicit, concrete, and comprehensive: house, city, table, bed, family, gate — all of it is either His gift or it is shav."
